Durban - The world continues to mourn the life of ANC stalwart and freedom fighter, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela. Madikizela-Mandela was born Nomzamo Winifred Zanyiwe Madikizela on September 26, 1936, in the village of Mbongweni, Bizana in the Transkei. While working as the first black medical social worker at Baragwanath Hospital, she exposed to the abject poverty under which most people were forced to live, she started to become politicised. In 1958, she married the late former president Nelson Mandela.   To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. Nomzamo Winifred Zanyiwe Madikizela, born on September 26, 1936, in the village of Mbongweni, Bizana in the Transkei, would become "Mother of the Nation." Video: Thobeka Ngema  In October 1958, Winnie took part in a mass action which mobilised women to protest against the Apartheid government’s pass laws. Winnie was arrested, banned and placed in solitary confinement by the Apartheid government, trying to keep her quiet. In 1969, Winnie became one of the first detainees under Section 6 of the notorious Terrorism Act. Once she said to the authorities, “you cannot intimidate people like me anymore.”  In 1976, following her activities during the uprising by school children protesting the introduction of Afrikaans as the language of instruction. In February 1990, when Nelson Mandela was freed from prison, they walked hand in hand. In September 2016, she celebrated her 80th birthday in Cape Town. On April, 2 she died at Milpark Hospital in Johannesburg after a long illness. (Additional reporting: ANA) (Source: South African History Online)  Daily News